english:
  title: Epitaph for the Honored Official Hyeonbok Gun, Kwon Yeom, with Preface
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Kwon clan traces its origins to Kim Haeng, a great family of Silla. He served as magistrate of Bokju, and when the founder of Goryeo, after establishing his throne, marched against Silla and reached Bokju, Haeng recognized the will of heaven and surrendered the entire district. The founder rejoiced, saying, "Haeng truly possesses the wisdom of expediency," and bestowed upon him the surname Kwon. In generations thereafter, many illustrious men emerged from this line. The문淸公 Hyeon achieved great renown; the 국재선생 Bo, who held the position of Chief Minister and 첨의찬성사, excelled in letters and virtue above all his contemporaries; and the 송재선생 Jun was enfeoffed as Duke of Gilchang, establishing an office with capable subordinates. Through humility, respect for righteousness, and excellence in managing his household, he drew the admiration of the entire nation. These three generations successively served as director of examinations, and many of their disciples rose to prominence. Thus those who envied wealth and admired propriety all turned toward the Kwon clan. The Ui Mausoleum took the Public's daughter as Subi, and the Yeong Mausoleum took the Public's sister's daughter, a woman of the Hong clan, as Hwabi—both acts showing how deeply the Kwon clan was honored.

    Although the Public rose to glory through his family's standing, his heart took little pleasure in rank. He cherished righteousness above all, and for this the world held him in high esteem. The Public's name was Yeom, with the courtesy name Sayeom. His father, the 송재선생, married the daughter of the 밀직사 O Inyeong, and the Public was born in the winter of the tenth month, Gimja year of Daeduk. At age ten he was appointed to the 함경전녹사. In the Gimja year of Yeonwu he was promoted to 별장, and the following year was selected as 보마배행수. Shortly thereafter he rose to 낭장. In the Jeongsa year he traveled to the Yuan capital. In the Muo year he was appointed 삼사부사, elevated to 봉상대부, and that summer returned to Goryeo. In the Gyehae year of Jichi he traveled again to the capital and presented himself before the Yuan emperor. In the Gapja year of Taejeong he was promoted to 중정대부사복정. The following year, through imperial decree, he received appointment as 선무장군, 합포진변만호부만호—a hereditary post. The year after, he was appointed 응양군대호군, and subsequently became 선군별감, fairly dividing the land by regulation so that the people found it beneficial. In the Musin year of Cheonlyeok he traveled to the capital, and in the Gyeong-o year of Jisun returned to Goryeo, where he was appointed 정순대부좌상시. Later, in the Eulhae year of Zhiyuan, he was enfeoffed as 현복군—a post given because his broad-minded nature inclined him away from administrative affairs.

    In the Jeongchuk year he built a pavilion beside the lotus pond at Sunggyo-ri and named it 운금루. The Minister Yi Sunmin wrote its commemorative inscription. Whenever flowers bloomed, he would prepare elaborate feasts, invite distinguished guests, and offer wine in honor of his father, while all his descendants gathered in joy. People of the time deeply admired this practice. In the spring of the Muin year, the 의릉 said, "The Honored Official Hyeonbok may counsel on matters of state." Thereupon the Public was promoted to 광정대부첨의찬성사. At this time Yang Jae of Yannan enjoyed the favor of the ruler. The Public despised his character and would not associate with him according to propriety. Yang Jae harbored deep resentment and used his influence to obstruct the Public's advancement. The following year the Public was again enfeoffed as 현복군. After one year, the Public died of illness at his home on the seventh day of the fourth month, the Gyeongsin year.

    The 정헌공 Wang Hu, the Public's uncle, wept and said: "Among the descendants of the Kwon clan, none surpassed the 만호 in virtue. I long hoped he would shelter our family. Why did heaven so swiftly deprive us of such a worthy son?" The 정헌공, being a man of discernment who flattered none, possessed keen judgment of character, and through him we may know the Public's worth.

    The Public, though born to wealth and comfort, spurned ostentation. He attended all celebrations and condolences personally. When he mourned at another's funeral, he showed no distinction between kinsman and friend, appearing in black cap and white robe with sorrow evident upon his face. Observers were moved by his sincerity and felt themselves unable to match it. Throughout his life he excelled at friendship and, encountering others' hardships, exerted himself to their rescue, withdrawing only when matters were resolved. Though he enjoyed feasts and wine, he took no pleasure in music or courtesans. He was skilled at archery and horsemanship; hunting without guile, he achieved abundant success, earning praise from all the martial men. What brought him least joy was rank and office. To gain his parents' love and his friends' regard was his greatest desire.

    Those whom the Public served and befriended included the Minister Yi Sunmin, the Marquis Jang Sunggong of Hwain, the Minister Hong of Yangpa, An Sangheun, An Geunjae, Hong Dangseong, Kim Eonayang, Min Geubam, Choe Julongs, the Evaluator Yi Gwon, and the Privy Counselor Pae Cheongyeong—all eminent men of the age renowned for letters, governance, horsemanship, and archery, whom people even now revere. The Public, moving in their circle, acquired their ways as if by nature. He also engaged the late Minister Kim Ilbong to teach him the Mongol language, in which he became quite proficient. Such was the beauty of his native talents. Yet why did heaven deny him long life?

    When the Public passed, his grandparents and parents remained living. What must have been their hearts? And as the Public's life came to its end, his thoughts turning to his grandparents and parents—what anguish must have filled him then? Alas, how sorrowful!

    His wife, Lady Zhao, was the daughter of 도첨의찬성사 and 정헌공 Zhao Lyeon. Though widowed in her youth, she governed her sons with propriety, earning the praise of her kinfolk. More than thirty years have passed since the Public's passing. All his sons achieved high office and maintained the family's honor. Even in the nine springs below, his spirit surely rejoices. When the Public departed, I was but thirteen years old. Who could have foreseen that a child of thirteen would hold the brush to compose the epitaph of his noble hall? Alas, these are matters to stir the heart.

    All the Public's sons enjoyed close friendship with me, and they came seeking this epitaph. I hereby record the family lineage, the offices held, and the descendants.

    The eldest son, Yong, received the appointment of 선무장군, 합포진변만호부만호중대광현성군. The second son, Hyeon, received the appointment of 왕부단사관봉익대부판도판서상호군. The third son, Ho, holds the rank of 봉익대부전법판서상호군. The fourth son, Gyun, received the appointment of 선수봉의대부융상제점소제점봉익대부전공판서상호군. The youngest son, Ju, holds the rank of 중정대부삼사좌윤진현관직제학지제교.

    The eldest daughter is Subi. The second daughter married Yuan's 한림학사승지영록대부 Budashili. The third daughter married the 봉익대부판전의사사 O Junghwa. The fourth daughter married the 중정대부전의령보문각직제학지제고 Yeom Gukbo. The youngest daughter married the 선수정동행중서성도진무사도진무충근찬화공신광정대부정당문학진현관대제학지춘추관사상호군 Won Songsun.

    There are several grandsons and granddaughters. The 현성군 had two sons and four daughters. The eldest son, Jun, serves as 행수별장. The second son, Yeon, holds the rank of 산원. The eldest daughter married 별장 Min Liang. The second daughter married 중랑장 Song Insoo. The youngest daughter remains in her maiden home. The 단사관 had one son and five daughters. The son, Suan, studies at the National University. The eldest daughter married 도제고판관 Kim Gyun. The second daughter married 보마배행수별장 Park Jaon. The third daughter married 별장 Kim Ulbu. The remaining daughters are young. The 판서 had three sons and two daughters. The eldest son, Jing, serves as 행수낭장. The second son, Hwan, is a 성균진사. The third son, Dam, serves as 전보도감녹사. The eldest daughter married 좌우위록사 Hong Huichung. The second daughter married 별장 Han Hyup. The 제점 had one son and two daughters. The son, Hong, studies at the National University. The daughters are young. The 좌윤 had two sons and one daughter. The eldest son is Hun and the second is Sik, both young; the daughter is also young.

    Among the external descendants, the 승지 had one son and one daughter. The son is Seupdeuryeo; the daughter is young. From the O clan: one son and four daughters. The son, Jebo, serves as 흥복도감녹사. The daughters are young. From the Yeom clan: two sons and one daughter. The eldest son, Jijung, serves as 목릉직. The second son, Jihwa, serves as 창릉직. The daughter is young. From the Won clan: two sons. The eldest son, Seo, serves as 박두점녹사. The second son, Sang, serves as 사경원판관.

    The Public is buried west of the Great Peace Temple in Gaeseong County.

    The epitaph reads:

    Filial to his parents,
    Trusted by all men,
    Honored with rank and enfeoffment—
    His person shone with glory.
    The Son of Heaven sighed and
    Bestowed upon him the tiger seal,
    He carried forward his noble house,
    Its light spreading across the eastern seas.
    Many have borne many sons and lived long,
    Such things are common in this world—
    Yet for the Public alone
    It remained unfulfilled.
    Who thwarted the heavens' plan?
    Only the favor of an age,
    Unless the man prove worthy,
    Comes not heavy with esteem.
    Though his grave may lie desolate,
    The Public's name shall not fade away.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Kwon Yeom served during the late Goryeo period under Mongol Yuan influence; many of his positions reflect the hybrid administrative system of that era.
  - key: ''
    value: The Cloud Brocade Pavilion (운금루) was a place where the Public gathered family and dignitaries to honor his father—a Confucian practice of filial piety.
  - key: ''
    value: The epitaph's regret that the Public died without achieving long life and many years reflects the Confucian ideal of receiving Heaven's blessings through virtue.
  - key: ''
    value: Yi Saek, the author, was only thirteen when Kwon Yeom died; he would later become one of Goryeo's most celebrated scholars and officials.
